			<ns0:name>mmau...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/115895631343942902873/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">ARM Sandbox allows read of arbitrary memory addresses. This could allow the access of trusted data, which may frequently contain data that should not be exposed to the NaCl plugin (at minimum the username would be exposed via paths, but much worse data could be exposed depending on the design of the runtime).

This is easy to detect, just ldr an abritrary address.

This is currently present for speed reasons (masking reads was considered too expensive). This bug is primarily intended to remind people to take care when designing the runtime before ARM release to minimize the impact of this bug.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2013-01-11T20:03:28.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2011-08-03T05:02:30.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Fixed</ns2:status><ns2:owner>
